"Abstract At a luncheon meeting of the Congressional Internet Caucus Advisory Committee Forum on 28th September, Congressman Curt Weldon (Republican — Pennsylvania) revealed that high-level deal-making on access to encrypted data had taken place between the Pentagon/national security community and IBM and Microsoft. The main subject of the caucus was the hotly debated new US government encryption export and use policy announced by the White House on 16 September 1999. The new policy de-licenses encryption products below either 56 or 64 bits, depending on the type, and calls for a one-time meaningful technical review for crypto in excess of 56 or 64 bits. Technical review periods would be kept to an average of 30 days. One-time reviews would be done for retail products not requiring extensive installation or maintenance support and other custom products that do. After a one-time review, no more export licenses would be required. However, export of cryptographic source code would still require a special license. After receiving a general export license, following the one-time review, vendors would have to provide post-export reports to the government. Individual licenses would still be required for exports to certain government and military agencies. In addition, encryption exports are banned to seven terrorist states (known as the ‘T7’)."
